A Republican strategy to counter the re-election of Obama
The leaders of the Republicans justify their policies with the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth by affirming that the election fraud in the United States is more rare than the number of people killed by the lightning strike.
Incidentally, the Republican lawyers have recorded only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the turnout.
In this sense, these measures are partly undermining the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the US states are responsible for the conduct of elections in the individual states.
In this sense, since 2009, the majority of American governments have announced new laws that make registration or urn entry more difficult.
Following the November 2010 elections, 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states were able to register this phenomenon.
As a result, 180 draft laws were introduced in 2011 alone which restrict the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo identification and proof of US citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the time-limits for the early vote, declare the right to register as voters on the election day invalid, and give citizens the right to vote for which a legal act exists.
Before the 2006 elections, no US state required voters to show a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to raise such a demand.
The Supreme Court of the United States confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of the law of Indiana.
The Republican authorities rushed to extend this practice to other states.
Over the last two years, they promoted draft laws in 34 federal states that force voters to show a photo identification.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, US citizens do not have a universal card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of US citizens, i.e. 21 million persons entitled to vote, do not have a photo ID issued by a government authority of their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a card.
However, there are often more than a hundred dollars to be paid to obtain the required ID.
Young people, minorities and people with low incomes are disproportionately affected by the new restrictions.
In fact, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people with less than $35,000 income, 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have the required photo ID.
This is far more than that.
Students who are regarded as voters, who are increasingly voting for democratic candidates, are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their institution in several countries.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting associations who choose more closely for the Republican side to use the cards issued by these associations for elections.
Before 2004, no state called for the election of citizenship.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove their US citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting hispanic voices.
Because it is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the democratic party.
In addition, Republican legislators in 2011 have promoted laws in eight states that have abolished the registration of voters on election day.
In addition, you have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the campaigns to register voters in the 2004 general elections have helped to register about 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the number of new voters in 2010 by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, the Republican legislators in five other states have adopted laws aimed at shortening the time period for the early vote.
For example, in the 2008 general elections in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were Afro-Americans, although they account for only 13% of the voters of the state.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter accounted for only 11% of the voters, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, the whites representing 76% of the voters made up only 46% of the voters who chose in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed the adoption of laws that restrict the registration of voters.
Several draft laws were blocked by the vetos of democratic governors.
The US Attorney General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They could partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo identification.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make the exercise of the right to vote more difficult.
The democratic critics denounce the party political nature of the passed laws and see in them as a clear goal the influence of the results in the states that are decisive for 2012.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that those states that have passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes required by the electoral body to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these changes to the electoral system legislation will have a significant impact on the outcome of the presidential elections in 2012.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the turnout.
In this sense, these measures are partly undermining the democratic system of the United States.
Early detection of prostate cancer: should the test be performed or not?
