In the studies conducted in the USA, there were numerous disruption factors between control groups, making it difficult to interpret these data and make clear recommendations.
Another study, this time from Europe, concluded that there is a difference in the mortality of patients with and without early detection.
This study has also shown that the probability of metastases forming after 12 years is 30 to 40% higher when no early detection has been performed.
That is why I recommend the test from the age of 50 or 40 if you have a direct relative who has already been suffering from prostate cancer.
In men of African-American origin, there is also a higher risk.
The most important thing is to make the right decision once a cancer has been diagnosed.
There are cancers that are aggressive and others that are indolent.
The patient must really understand the extent of the risk of his cancer by showing him the possible options in which prostate cancer can remain untreated if it does not affect the quality of life in the long term, and in these cases it is more likely to be decided to actively monitor the disease.
Today, many men who have known cancer do not receive treatment because their cancer is not aggressive and does not pose a threat to their lives.
They are proposed to be actively monitored and treated as they progress.
It is with increasing accuracy that the criteria for a decision are defined, who should be treated and who not.
That is why I still recommend carrying out the test.
The most important thing, however, is to talk to his doctor to determine whether he should be performed or not.
