The Higgs Boson Analyzes
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson has aroused a certain amount of excitement last summer, and this for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this Boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism that is responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence was predicted by the standard model - our best or "lowest false" explanation of nature and the behaviour of matter - but not yet empirically observed.
But for the physicists, it's not completely sure that it's really about the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of doubt that we have a real new particle and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented at a major physics conference in Kyoto this week, but there is still no data to be absolutely sure about it.
Nevertheless, let us assume that this is actually the Higgs, as there seems to be only a small risk of being deceived, and let us look at what it is about.
There is an indispensable law in this world that causes two objects not to be present at the same place at the same time.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and do not try it too hard as you will be hurting yourself.
For even if particle physics is a truly strange world, it turns out that such a law applies to it as well: the Pauli exclusion principle, which means that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantity state", with this "state" largely consisting of some of its characteristics.
From this the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In a corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the Bosons, an evil gang of anarchists, who are nothing sacred - certainly not this principle, which means that they can actually be at the same place at the same time.
These bosons are divided into two groups according to the website The Particle Adventure from the Berkeley laboratories (which by the way is absolutely amazing): the mesons that we will not treat here and the "power particles", through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
But it must be emphasized here that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as you might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of exceptional banality: the photon or the "light particle", which is the "bottom" of the electromagnetic force.
If a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes the direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" at this very place, in about like a pebble that was thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
Stabilised field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" so that this boson appears.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, a little like a frozen pond, whose surface could only be crushed by a very large rock.
That's why a huge particle accelerator like the CERN is needed - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a volume of 27 km! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never keep by itself in the fridge.
And equally, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (like the photon) have no mass.
For what can all these research be "good", asks Mrs. Plamondon?
For science, they are used to review the standard model (SM) and they also enable physicists to carefully examine all deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who most eagerly hope that such deviations are found, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and plug some holes in the model.
One has to say that the latter still has great defects, as it offers no explanation for gravity (ups!) and the dark matter, which constitutes about 80% of the matter of the universe (again ups!).
However, such deviations have not been found in the CERN so far.
Impacts
The impact of these research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there was no such thing.
By the way, in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, in which the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who developed the first permanent laser (the first were pulsated) in 1962 himself - has already told us that the laser was initially considered to be a "laboratory".
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also result from all the instruments surrounding research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in optics in 1969.
Although it was not the original purpose, today this sensor serves all digital cameras worldwide as an "eye" and has won the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily change our lives, but it means that you can never really know it...
Palliative care - the best way to die...
Quebec has recently discussed with its Committee on "Death in Dignity" the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate must be resumed shortly, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to take a closer look at this.
A few weeks ago Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that devoured him had allowed him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I did seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed in the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"However, it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it," he says.
The disease does its work: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he consents to let himself be helped in eating.
Courageously he can even smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medications, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to heal my diarrhea, as this is humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"Over the course of our lives, we learn that a man is peeping in the stand," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at Victor-Gadbois' home.
Returning to the childhood phase is an unacceptable humiliation for certain people.
"That depends on the person's ability", he notes, taking a step back.
Because, in the opinion of several people working in palliative care, major events take place in the midst of this setback.
The patients who are admitted to the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois all suffer from cancer.
You have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, the doctors and nurses who care for them will no longer overcrowd them with so-called "healing" care.
For Mrs. A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die "consciously and through suffocation".
But through the illness I really got to know my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I don't have any more desires in my life," she says before she accepts the idea of putting on a mask to help her breathe.
She still expects a last visit from her son, who comes from Italy, in the next few days.
At the home of Victor-Gadbois you can offer a group of volunteer body care and help with food intake.
Palliative care is then used if there are no other possibilities.
To make dying more pleasant.
At 11,700 inhabitants in Quebec, there is a bed for palliative care.
That's very little, considering that one day we'll all die.
Here life is continued under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors in the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
Depending on your wishes, you give the deceased a mouth care with Brandy or Pepsi.
Diabetes patients should no longer control their blood sugar level.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died during the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help family members and patients alike," reports Nathalie Savard.
Victor-Gadbois is not a day like the other.
In addition to an old man of 93 years who enjoys the last family reunion in the courtyard and is well supported by his pillows, as one approaches to his honor, a young man of 36 years, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two small children, dies tragically after trying everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have always been used for cancer patients under the age of 45," says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of the patients admitted to the home Victor-Gadbois come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. to care to alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the end stage of their lives, both at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the home Victor-Gadbois and the Society for Domestic Palliative Care in the Greater Montreal area, are more or less exclusively specialized in the care of cancer patients.
Just this great inadequacy in the health care of Quebec ensures that several doctors specialised in palliative care look forward to the adoption of a law regulating death care and assisted suicide with concern.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by prominent personalities of palliative care such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s health system is not efficient enough to ensure that everyone has a right to high-quality palliative care before accepting to go to death care.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who had 14 days of severe pain in the emergency room without taking measures to alleviate them.
I fear that patients only want to die because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients in spite of worst predictions bitten to the last day.
Hélène Richard's chances of survival were already minimal when she stopped a difficult chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she replied that she regretted that I was giving up the fight, she told me.
However, she had told me that I was at the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the caregiver for not accepting this request after their pain has been eased by a team of palliative care.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent in pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care of the community of residential palliative care of the large Montreal area, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
Thus, at the very end of life, the doctors often resort to the terminal sedation, which leads to the patient sleeping either sporadicly or permanently until the time of his death.
We can no longer act as if we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will be increasingly able to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not alleviated say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean, "I want you to put me to sleep," but "I want my pain to be alleviated."
