With Bitcoin you can pay and sell without a bank
The opposite of the current monetary exchange based on central banks, identified transactions and handling fees between the parties.
Moreover, as is so often the case in these technologies, a political vision is tangible: the conviction that the current monetary system, shaped by bank monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, the bitcoin invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym) is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros, etc.) and a protocol for safe exchange such as BitTorrent, which enables the direct exchange of files.
With 15,000 computers on the network, some 200,000 transactions have already been recorded.
Some thousands of websites accept Bitcoin as a donation or as a means of payment.
After reaching a peak of $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, Bitcoin's rate fell to $2 five months later, before recovering to around $10 today (the rates are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to the world trade of real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success", "in competition with the dollar or euro" and "similar to the traditional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as the "Credits" that are used to advance in a video game that you can win or buy by playing (and sometimes also exchange back).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trade is checked and processed by a central authority every time.
With Bitcoin, all net notes are simultaneously held by the account book, auditors, money issuers as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses in the form of an email.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures the anonymity.
A series of data related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
With the help of the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are present in the public accounts billing book that is distributed throughout the network.
The decisive step is to enter this new transaction in this book.
This is done through a mathematical task that is started on the computers, whereby the winner, who is a kind of preliminary central banker, has the privilege to add this additional line.
It is a fragment of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
The computer "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole thing is "hacked".
The goal is to find the number that produces a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number has been found, the other nodes can easily check whether it is right.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If one user wants to pay with the same money twice (less than 10 minutes) for fraud, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other will remain unconnected, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task gets 50 bitcoins.
In order to prevent inflation, this reward will be halved regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The Bitcoins in circulation are therefore limited to 21 million, but are only divisible by one hundred million, leaving some room for manoeuvre...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with any improvement of the computing power.
The life of the network has already had heights and depths.
The websites providing services for Bitcoin were attacked and the bitcoin deposits were stolen.
"The vulnerability used does not concern the actual protocol," assures Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a company for real money payment and uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering using this anonymous service.
However, cash also shows these shortcomings.
Important actors like Wikipedia refuse to donate this kind.
They are accepted by others like the blog platform WordPress.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the invoice book and showed that almost 80% of the bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, a "Mega Lock Sales" was launched.
"Three thousand dollars have been exchanged," says Jon Holmquist, who works for the company Coinabul, who converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book about this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
His system Paytunia corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate the transactions that are thus cheaper.
In addition, the holder manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented by dealers, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just have to specify an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, Pierre Noizat, who assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend in the coverage of hierarchical systems in favour of more horizontal systems.
"It will take some time until Bitcoin prevails, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
Incidentally, the ECB's report provides for a reassessment of the various risks which are today highly regarded in the event of the success of this currency.
