A Constitution With the Breaking Bar in Egypt
It is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt remains more than ever divided as regards the declaration of constitutional power that temporarily grants it unlimited authority, it has decided to put everything on a map.
To surprise everyone, he announced on Wednesday that the constitutional assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State had granted this plenary two additional months for the completion of its work.
For almost two years now, Egypt has been relying on a provisional, multi-amended text, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only led to an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "stepping the law with his feet".
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time that compels the brothers to abandon their purpose to explain the text section by section to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way of restoring his public and democratic legitimacy while the protest rages throughout the country.
After confirmations in an interview with the American weekly show Time, Mohammed Mursi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote well.
In particular, with this recourse to an urgent vote, an ultimatum will be put to the Egyptian people: "either you vote for my draft or I retain the unlimited power of attorney," the latter should supposedly end after the adoption of the Constitution.
85 mostly Islamist members of this constitutional assembly adopted the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of liberals have not responded to the call.
Shortly before the Constitutional Declaration in mid-November, they turned away because they believe that they have not been able to bring their views into line.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
In order to reach a quorum, 11 people, deputy members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Moslem brothers.
It is not surprising that the articles have been adopted unanimously.
Incidentally, the commentators found it amusing that the only difference of opinion of the day... was expressed at the time for prayer, since some members of the body felt that the pendulum was not exactly what was going on in the constitutional assembly.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which drew all attention to itself, finally remains identical with that of the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of justice".
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made it possible to apply more strictly.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their good will and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
"Skin sanctity" returns the liberals, who see this only as a propaganda strike.
According to them, the Islamisation of the Constitution on other articles takes place.
In doing so, they have in particular Article 220 in mind, which confers an advisory role on the University of Al-Azhar, in particular with regard to the verification of compliance with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt's specialist Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing, since "the people who are asked for an opinion have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
You can see the first signs of a theocracy in this."
The fears of the liberals are also nourished by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be far less moderate than the present one.
"There is currently no concrete religious commitment.
With this Constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics who have been trained in part in the French system," says Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He admits, however, "that in relation to Article 220 there may be a ambiguity, since the terms used are rejected by the religious vocabulary.
This refers in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic case law, Note d. Red.].
And in the future, the question could be raised to what extent civil judges are competent to decide."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticised for the far-reaching powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Moslem brothers argue that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another issue: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the examination of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to the National Defence Council.
Similarly, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as the human rights defence associations have called for.
The latter also communicate their fears regarding the text which they consider to be a threat to freedom.
The practice of blasphemy is being maintained, and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for the right to free speech, especially for the press.
Furthermore, no more articles refer to the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In your opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
The supporters of the Head of State will march on Saturday.
In Israel Ukrainian tourists expect sacred places, the navel of the world and a sea of Sole
The Promised Land unites in itself the glory of Bible truths, modern comfort and a pristine nature.
The AIF mentions the five main reasons for a visit to Israel.
Bend the Holy Sites
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It means that everyone who swims in this river receives God's blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the transformation of water into wine at a wedding feast, the walking on the water, the breastfeeding of the seastorm and the fishing.
Here Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most of the shrines, however, are located in Jerusalem.
Here believers take the path of suffering or the crossroads of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins at the Roman fortress Antonia, Pretoria, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the grave church on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, according to the Christian view, is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands at the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree from which the cross for the crucifixion of Jesus was made grew.
In Jerusalem is also the most holy place of the Jews - the Lamentations Wall, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 A.D.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave papers with wishes that then come true.
Make a trip in the heights
The ruins of the Fortress Massada form the remains of the secret hiding place from enemies, which Herod the Great built for his family in 25 A.D.
They are located on a rock wall in the mountains at 450 meters altitude above sea level.
Only climbers can reach the ruins from their own strength.
Everyone else will take an air cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at 1600 to 2040 meters altitude is the famous ski resort Hermon, where it attracts countless tourists during the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an old legend, pagan gods supposedly lived at the summit.
Visiting Unique Museums
In this country there are almost 300 museums.
Not all of them can be visited on one trip.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be paid a visit.
Among these is once the Israel Museum near the Knesset (parliament).
There, ancient Qumran manuscripts or scrolls of the Dead Sea, found in rock caves in the Judean desert, are kept and about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
There the collection of works by the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso is exhibited.
In Akko you can visit the museum in the Bad Al Basha, which houses several rooms of ancient Turkish baths with sculptures by the then visitors and bathers.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are neither museum guides nor souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are rejected in principle.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most disturbing chapters of history.
The most impressive section is the monument for the children, which was built to commemorate the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
When entering space, complete darkness prevails.
Stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and of the countries in which they died shall be heard.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Do Something for Health
The three main recreational areas of Israel are located on the banks of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of the three places there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Amazingly, the Red Sea also bathes in the winter months, as the water temperature does not fall below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and is bathed all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea with a position of 417 meters below sea level is the lowest sea in the world.
Its turquoise-blue water has a high salinity and thus carries even non-swimming on the surface without any problem.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt salts) and health sludge, as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, and the soothing of damaged nerves.
Touching the Secrets of Antiquity
These secrets hide the old town of Tel Aviv, the town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city the famous sea route, Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia, was connected.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark right here, and here Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda with which he lived a long and happy life.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets, named after astrological signs.
Fortuna should be the legend of all who touch the walls in the street with their star sign.
In Jaffa you can meet newlywed couples from all over Israel and even other countries at photo appointments.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can walk through the Roman theater and conquer the fortress of the Knights of the Cross.
In Roman times Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and the residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
Today, evening concerts and operas are performed in the carefully restored theatre.
Favourites for tourists
If you go to Israel, don't worry about your poor English skills: about 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the trip is not taken in euros, but in dollars that can simply be changed into shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you usually get on the bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a high-speed train and in Haifa the only metro line in the country with six stations connecting the sub-city to the upper city.
In fact, it is an underground cable car.
A journey within the city costs 6 Shekel regardless of the mode of transport, which is sufficient for a journey of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturday.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport rests.
And on Sunday morning the working week begins.
In many cafés, restaurants and restaurants, only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, marine products, fish without dandruff and food containing both milk and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice between various dishes with mutton and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls of pure beans and peas (falafel) as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no straying dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
For this there are many well-nourished cats who stroll through the streets comfortably and unhinderedly.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parking cars.
The cats like lively places and don't say no to delicacies.
One car rental costs between 37 dollars per day (Hyundai Getz) and 188 dollars (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
The insurance costs an additional 15 dollars a day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels a day.
Tickets for museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
In figures
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreation seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, which corresponds to an increase of 51% compared to the comparative period in 2010, prior to the lifting of the visa requirement on February 9, 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" leads to Moscow: Migrants save money for language
While MEPs and citizens are discussing the benefits of the law on mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals are already dealing with counterfeit certificates
Every year 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of families who remain in their home country.
A law came into force on 1 December, according to which every migrant worker must pass a test certifying the knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this scheme applies only to migrants who want to work in the services sector, in the municipal housing industry and in the retail trade.
However, the tests will become mandatory for all guest workers over time, according to the Federal Migration Authority.
Not only do you have to take language tests, but you also have to take tests into Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated for both the receipt and the extension of the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries in which Russian is the official language.
Also excluded from this law are persons who received their certificates and diplomas before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Meaning, problem and protection of rights
The total number of examination posts will be under the aegis of the Puschkin Institute for Russian Language, the Russian University of International Friendship, Moscow State University, Saint Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take the tests in all cities; already more than 160 relevant centres have been opened in Russia.
The initiative to launch the tests was supported by the members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
On the other hand, before the entry into force of the law in the press, civil rights activists asked the following question several times: what does the whole thing actually mean?
What changes does the requirement to show language skills bring, both for the Russians and for the guest workers?
Above all, responding to speakers from the Migration Authority, it is about reducing the number of forced workers.
"Many are now talking about the protection of the rights of migrant workers," says Viktor Sebelev, Head of the Representation of the Federal Migration Authority in Tajikistan.
However, their rights must already be protected from their departure.
Only organized recruitment will solve the problems of foreign workers to 90%.
Migrants face problems without work, education, language skills and medical evaluation.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably meet people with evil intentions who will put him under the pretext of help in a dark, narrow barracks, where he will endure with dozens of his equal months without food and documents and will train him 12 to 14 hours a day.
We reach many complaints from our migrants.
"In your home country, the One is promised to you, and upon arrival you will cheat, get their passports taken off and not receive the promised wage," confirms the head of the Labour Migration Board of the Tajikistan Migration Authority, Tolib Schwaripow.
Don't yell, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to earn their money in Russia admit that they cannot control not only the language of the target country but can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as the evil: Only a few Turkmen, Usbeken and Tajik can afford even a reasonable primary education.
For in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As a teenager, these children immediately take the first opportunity to earn money.
"It is difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Citizen's lawyers stress the following important aspect of the law.
Only migrants with legal status must pass the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no test and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, the majority of the guest workers continue to be illegally resident in Russia.
"Welcome" or "No access for unauthorised persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic obstacles and, of course, the linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The Russian police staff know that our documents are mostly forged and we are not registered, and then there are cases of blackmail.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," says Tajikie Umed Huschkadamov to journalists.
"Do not fear the cost of false papers only"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of migrants could have been falsified.
Some false certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Authority.
The falsified papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive them for free: every migrant who hoped to save himself the tests paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: this costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The fact that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption, so that the certificates cannot be easily purchased, both civil servants and citizens agree.
For the time being, the authorities can only promise guest workers who will pass the test for the first time that they will be given time for a basic language course.
In addition, new arrivals without language skills are offered jobs in areas where active communication with people is not necessary.
Interior Ministry Ignores Illegal Arms Market
Low share of legal weapons in crime
The Russian Ministry of the Interior is planning to tighten up the Arms Act for private arms owners.
The authorities thus react to recent events: Injured at shootings at weddings as well as seven dead at the amok run by Moscow lawyer Dmitri Winogradow.
The police want to ban the carrying of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was supported by the Chairman of the Duma Committee on Security and Corruption, Irina Jarrowaja, and promised that the amendments to the Arms Act will be presented shortly by the Duma.
Not all are satisfied that the Russian authorities want to fight the problems by "drawing the screws".
An open letter was published on the Internet, whose author - representatives of various arms associations - calls on the authorities to refrain from "sinless intensifications".
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very low, said the criminal lawyer, Wasilij Lesnikov, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed during six months in 2012, while a total of 1,168 thousand crimes were committed for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that a tightening of the law for private arms owners will not prevent criminals from using themselves in the black market.
Currently, according to the authors, in Moscow any weapon can be found for little money.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior stresses that the spread of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from the factories to the officers
The weapons reach the black market via several channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts arms orders
The first channel is the army or the military, i.e. weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," Baranez says.
On the second channel come illegal weapons that are stolen from criminals' order guards.
Baranez explains that these include weapons stolen from both police arms chambers and directly from law enforcement staff.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military arms camps.
There were frequent explosions in many military camps.
"There is evidence that in some cases it was arson to cover up the lack of weapons," says the former military member.
According to Baranez, weapons manufacturers also contribute to the black market.
"Today, there are countless private armament factories that do not stand up to international competition and therefore throw away the weapons under hand on the black market, for example in Moscow," the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many pistols and guns come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is an own, sometimes craftsmanship production and a mafia that organizes the smuggling," explains the former military.
Where did the guns come from?
Experts calculated the proportion of each of the five channels in supplying the black market with illegal weapons.
In 2011, a report was prepared by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Government Administration.
The experts analysed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, Criminological Literature and publicly available data on arms portals.
According to the investigators, the majority of illegal weapons originate from the army and the judicial authorities.
Half of all the weapons in the black market were there because of the "debt of those responsible for their work with weapons", says the report.
According to the data of the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from conflict zones, 14% from thefts in the production of weapons, and 5% from illegal excavations.
A sales advisor to an arms store who does not want to be mentioned by name assures us that weapons found in illegal excavations have long been bought by no one since they are outdated.
According to him, it is more common for traders to obtain the supply in an arms camp.
A gun, such as a TT-type gun, is bought via a enemy.
The weapon is displayed and handed over through the fence.
"The dealer takes the gun to the city and sells it there for 900 euros per piece with two magazines," he says.
"The police, of course, know everything and, therefore, if they cannot comply with the crime detection plan, periodically carry out control purchases from dealers offering illegal weapons," the sales consultant adds.
"Like in the luxury store"
Buyers and sellers find the most common about acquaintances with each other.
I had looked at websites and blogs when someone came to my attention and suggested that I come to the "Begowaja" station, where a person would wait for me to take me to a certain place, where we could then negotiate the price.
I only learned the price of the gun there
