Poland and space.
Last week, at a Council of Ministers meeting of the Member States of the European Space Agency (ESA), Poland was admitted as the 20th member of this Space Agency. Poland is thus the second member country from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became an ESA member on 12 November 2008.
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland's path to space, of course, began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmo enthusiasts were concerned with space travel, and they did not always meet with understanding.
I recall, for example, the lecture by A. Šternfeld on 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (b. 1905) left the audience cold, and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch sponsored by Robert Esnaut-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch in 1934 for "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
In Polish magazines he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's worldwide recognized contribution to the development of space travel was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters was named after him on the earth-facing side of the moon.
Already in 1925 a railway draisine was built in Poland for which a rocket drive was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to start or brake the Draisine.
The information to this effect comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-powered shots.
The research led the Institute Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
The documents submitted show that research has progressed to the stage of practical testing.
The research was then, of course, interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, a photoelectric hunting kite was designed by Ing. Rohoziński in the press, and the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of the rocket drive.
Shortly before the war, all projects for military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Doradczo-Naukovy Committee).
The committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of work his work was completed from the start of the war.
Further articles on space travel appeared after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this society is made in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles of space travel are dedicated.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal for the creation of a space company.
At the time, there were already the first satellite technology projects, and it was to be avoided that the exploration of space would have a future.
As early as 1956, the Polish space company PTA tried to join the International Space Federation, founded in 1951, and in fact, PTA became a regular member in the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), was appointed Vice-Chairman of the International Space Federation.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has played a major role in the development of the most successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologicczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first start took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959, flight tests began in the Błędów desert with the two-stage RM-2 rocket.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another level of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach an altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for the observation of high winds.
In 1962, however, the further development was discontinued.
The first RM rocket was replaced by the Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its overall length was 510 cm and its initial weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of rocket were developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket has a transport space with a capacity of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B has a capacity of 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C has a capacity of 0.62 litres.
The maximum altitude for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor 2 rockets were developed at the Aeronautical Institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were then built.
It is also worth mentioning the accession of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, on which two years later followed the establishment of a national COSPAR committee.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites as part of the Interkosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimir Remek.
