The movie Argo: If it's the worst thing to call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of protesting Islamist students occupied the US Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats as hostages.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the overthrown Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, who had kept the patronage of his regime for decades.
There was no positive way out of this situation for the American government - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have seriously damaged the trust of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, she was unable to enforce the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a severe blow to the reputation of the United States, and the subsequent failure in the violent attempt to liberate hostages only made everything worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been mediated by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages evoked at home a wave of solidarity as well as anti-Iranian moods.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the United States a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the message, six ambassadors managed to escape.
It ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees from Iran, helping them to cover up their true identity – they traveled with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film staff who allegedly visited film locations in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by the expert for "Exfiltration", Tony Mendez, also required the collaboration of Hollywood.
In order to make the cover credible, articles about this film project appeared in specialist journals, press conferences were held, and the fictitious production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have been kept secret for a long time, and the film is based on Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "caper movie", i.e. the history of a successful piece of housekeepers such as the movie Ocean's Eleven.
This changes the mood levels in the film - on the one hand the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and also in the film version of the same situations there are no big differences).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which come ironically and slightly out of focus.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the conference table, on the halls, on the telephone...
Ben Affleck has succeeded in a remarkable relaunch of his career with this film.
From a smiling actor has become a respectable director, and also as an actor he is no longer the goal of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the crime No children's play (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the thriller city without mercy (2010).
At the same time, it's Affleck's first film that doesn't play in the director's native Boston.
The feeling for the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics of this director's previous films from the Hollywood standard.
Affleck also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that have really taken place - the entrance sequence of the amazement of the message is very impressive in its clarity, and nevertheless conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictableness that occurs when the story moves somewhere.
Affleck has a similar effect with his team even in fictional scenes (the false film staff on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not actually offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
With the few, however, he works quite successfully, sometimes helping the reality a little - which then does not always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the impending crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted by a telephone call in America, or also the persecution hunt on the runway, seem somewhat artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its far too wide spread, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters would have earned more space, so they are not alone in the film.
Affleck’s film loses a bit of traction. It is a film that can be watched with some interest and the design and the retro-style, reminiscent of a thriller from the 70th century.
However, he only stirs up enthusiasm.
However, as a reminder of a piece of history still living in a certain way to this day, and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of the omnipotent and all-knowing secret services are, it is sufficient.
