The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which annually calls for a survey on the most absurd bank charges, has decided this year to organise the competition "The most absurd regulation or idea from the EU workshop".
"This idea was inspired by the recent EU plan to introduce a 40% female rate in the management of large European companies," said Patrik Nacher, who is responsible for organising this survey, in front of the Právo newspaper.
Among the nominees are, for example, the judgment of the European Court of Justice on the harmonization of insurance rates for men and women.
Until then, women enjoyed an advantage in life insurance because they objectively pose a lower risk to insurance companies.
"More incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be nominated by the end of this year.
The actual vote will then take place by the end of February 2013", Nacher informed.
Among the controversial EU regulations are the mandatory blending of bioethanol into fuels which are inherently harmful, the prohibition of reliable mercury thermometers only because they contain a relatively small amount of this dangerous substance, or also the directive on the size of chicken cages, which became significantly more expensive this year.
Criticism has in the past also reaped the actual ban on the use of the term "butter spread" or the ban on the sale of traditional light bulbs.
Bananas must be 14 cm long
The EU apparatus often decides under the pressure of this or that lobby from commerce and industry, whose demands are usually represented in Brussels by one or more member countries (the Czech Republic is currently trying to enforce the Czech banks' demands, for example, with the threat of veto).
Lobby interests also contributed to the fact that bananas of the highest commercial class in the EU must be at least 14 cm long and must not have "crushing anomalies".
In doing so, the European Commission defended itself by arguing that it merely harmonises the differing national standards which would hinder trade.
The EU's standards on fruit and vegetables have already been refuted by the opposition of some countries, indicating that the current directives would lead to a waste of food.
A candidate for victory in this survey may be the EU regulation of last year, which, according to balloons, must be given the indication that children under the age of eight must not inflate the balloon without the supervision of an adult.
The EU called for an American study which, according to balloons, is the leading cause of child suffocation.
A similar restriction already applies to children up to 14 years of age in the use of annual market streets.
Curiosity There are also ideas at home
