The Bankovnípoplatky.com server nominated, in cooperation with the Association of Liberal Economists Laissez Faire, in addition to the above-mentioned absurdities, the EU Regulation on the volume of food stocks in a Member State.
The EU thus established the maximum volume of food stocks that could be found on the day of our accession to the EU in the Czech Republic.
The Czech Republic then exceeded, for example, the fixed volume for canned mushrooms, which threatened us with a high fine.
The organisers of the survey were also impressed by the idea that certain countries should receive money for not having the sea, or for the idea of providing funding for applications for funding.
These ideas were, of course, not from Brussels, but from Prague.
"We are disadvantaged by the fact that we have no sea.
We will apply for a refund from the EU," said Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD) Minister for Agriculture in autumn 2004.
As an argument, he argued that the cereal harvest had been very high and the state stocks had been overcrowded as a result of the so-called intervention purchases.
As the Czech Republic has another way to seaports, according to Palas, the EU should pay us hundreds of millions of euros.
