Szabo: "Germans must play a bigger role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the inclusion of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, expert on US-European relations, Berlin is thus balancing to a narrow degree of diplomacy.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week Germany had initially signaled that it would vote against the request for an observer status of the Palestinians at the United Nations.
But then Berlin remained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be careful because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without, however, being too critical of Israel.
During the rebellion in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it was about establishing a no-fly zone.
This was finally enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is changing its foreign policy, away from a policy managed, as it were, by the United States, towards a German foreign policy.
Aggravatingly, Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
So the Germans find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that she is still working on her role, but they are on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy such as they have France or Great Britain.
What does a "normal" foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It shows the willingness to take positions in national interests that are independent of those of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of the other major powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests affected the attitude in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf States.
Therefore, it must be careful not to confront the public, but also the elites, in the Arab countries.
That certainly matters.
But I wouldn't want to give too much weight to that either, that's not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German deliberations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the United States by abstaining in important decisions, such as voting on Palestine?
I believe that in Europe and even in the United States there is a great deal of understanding of the German position.
That is why I do not believe that this was such a dramatic break as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even show some respect for it.
Because it signals that it is taken seriously as an international player and that its interests need to be taken into consideration.
There are various opinions in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
The US, on the other hand, has clearly voted for a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the United States and many European nations?
Because of American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I believe that under Obama the government has quite a lot of understanding of the European position.
But because of the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, represent this position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not as big as they always appear.
If you look at the relations between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not so thrilled by Netanyahu's policy.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the US on the one hand, and the position of the most important partners in the EU on the other?
I think that makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would, of course, be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, which is not the case at present.
So they can't be part of a wider line and have to push things out of their own position instead.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will take on a leading role in pushing Europe into a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, of course, even because of its relationship with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive issue.
But I think the Germans are aware that they need to play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as an important international player - does Germany even want to play a leading role?
Or does Germany still have a difficult leadership role?
Germany is not used to it yet, it is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a greater role.
For example, when we look at the euro crisis, every time Germany assumes a larger role, there will be a wide range of anti-German feelings.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
This is actually the old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this way, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It must be receptive to various neighbors and opinions and that is not easy.
Now the US's influence in European policy is steadily diminishing, but the EU is not filling this vacuum at the moment, who else is there?
