And because most of us today almost constantly stare at one screen or another, the benefits of boredom no longer benefit us.
So should we welcome the boredom with open arms?
Yes.
And no.
I'll come back to that again.
However many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively recent phenomenon that has developed with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at Calgary University in Canada and author of "Boredom: A Lively History" (Yale University Press, 2011) doesn't think so.
"In fact, boredom has a very long history," he says.
Pompeii's walls adorn a Latin graffiti about boredom dating back to the first century.
And then there is the question of how we define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After a long reading of research literature and the presentation of the idea in front of a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues concluded that boredom can be defined as the experience of "wanting to engage in a satisfying activity, but not being able to do so".
Boredom is therefore different from apathy in that the person is not busy, but wants to be.
On the other hand, there is no urge to do anything about the apathy.
The key experience of boredom, he says, exists in a "disruption of the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and the feeling that time is passing only slowly".
Boredom can listen to it almost as much as depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes that although these two conditions may be related, bored people see the problem in their environment or in the world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're boring, even if we're having trouble concentrating.
In her study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention" - to German for example: "The Idle Mind: The Definition of Boredom Under the Aspect of Attention", which appeared in September in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science", Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a volume on which a person was given a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud television program from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content. Others listened to it at a low volume, so it was hardly perceptible, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
The people who heard the barely audible television said to feel more bored than the other two groups - they had problems concentrating, could find no reason for them, and admitted their difficulties of boredom.
If one tries to focus on a difficult or strenuous task, the disturbance of attention can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, Associate Professor of Neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, if you do a monotonous activity - "like the search for faulty products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help not to feel bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that round tablets and chalks, often interpreted as signs of boredom, can even fight them by staying physically more attentive.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to fight around learn more and keep more information than those who are forced to sit still," says Professor Fenske.
We all get bored at some point - my late flight, a thunderous speaker, a particularly tiring movie.
But some people get bored more easily than others.
To measure these differences, researchers developed a "scale of boredom vulnerability" in the 1980s.
On the scale there are statements like "Many things I have to do, repeat and are monotonous" and "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything".
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys are often bored than girls, says Stephen Vodanovich, Professor of Psychology at the University of Westflorida - especially in terms of the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a rather tense bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted almost 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with a pager.
He found out that 32% of the adults in school and when doing homework were bored, whereas 23% said they were bored when they were not in school.
But only 3% of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he does not know whether the percentages of boredom have increased or decreased.
However, he is sure that "youth is found to be particularly boring", mainly because children and teenagers have no major influence on their everyday life.
So back to my question of origin: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases it causes people to take extreme physical risks and fall off gambling or drugs to alleviate them - that's what studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors investigate the relationship between boredom and creativity. This opinion is Professor Vodanovich, who has been investigating the subject for more than two decades.
"With boredom, the brain wants to tell you that something else should be done," says Gary Marcus, Professor of Psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn't always know what to do best.
If you're bored and you use this energy to play guitar and cook, you'll be happy.
However, television can provide a sense of happiness in the short term, but these flee again in the long run.
So if your bored child reaches an iPad, it can get rid of boredom. However, it has not learned to entertain or control itself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds: "Self-control is transferred from one situation to another".
The child not only learns to talk but also receives more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we see them too critically.
Instead, our aim should be to feel at ease even away from the constant revitalization of activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds like we have to be bored more often than not, but boredom is the painful, constant desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that people are really just looking for a way to turn off and relax.
"In an environment where we are constantly overstimulated, it is difficult to get busy when the noise is once muted."
