The most difficult occupation in the world: the human labor animals of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and their health if they carry 70 kilos of sulphur over the steep, rocky roads.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others work literally in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by extracting sulphur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
For this, it has to climb down to the bottom of its crater every day, where the sulfurous gas that flows out of the earth attaches itself to the air in contact with it.
After breaking out large sulphur stones that weigh up to 70 kilos in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the abominable stone paths.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to a height of 2386 meters, but the exhausted carriers need more than 40 minutes for the ascent at the tortoise, while maintaining the balance and carefully setting their steps so that they do not slip out and crash.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell down on the steep slopes of Kawah Ijen years ago.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 Eurocents for each kilo of sulphur they mine.
At the top, they pave the way between the tourists who photograph them like circus monkeys and walk with the tiresome heavy baskets three kilometers to the scale, which a mining company has set up a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, who since 1960 has exploited the deposits in the volcano and (never better said) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Eurocent) for each kilo of sulphur.
It then sells it to the petrochemical industry for every 10,000 rupees (83 Eurocents) because this mineral is widely distributed in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even bleaching sugar.
"Since we normally carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each way," explains Anto, who normally makes three routes a day.
For each route it takes three hours to complete it, but at the end of the day it has 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros).
What looks like a miserable wage for such a seemingly inhuman effort, however, is the triple of what he would earn with the field work.
"The daily wage of the miners here, where 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) are paid a day at the coffee harvest and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high," explains the carrier, who previously worked as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the work was not as hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village nearby, and that for a reason as important as the sulphur in Indonesia: "I have married a Bali girl where they are Hindus, and I have brought her to Java to convert her to Islam."
Anto has asthma, breathing with difficulty, coughing frequently and his eyes are irritated by the poisonous gases.
For three years, 27-year-old Anto has been risking his life on Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already left the first traces of him, even though he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, breathing with difficulty, coughing frequently and his eyes are irritated by the poisonous gases from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay for the attainment of his dream.
"I will work here for two years because I want to open a shop or learn Spanish or French," he promises in more than just acceptable English.
This sympathetic and intelligent but life-punished young man could work as a tourist guide, waiter or at the reception of a hotel, but instead he does the work of a tragedy.
He splits a dirty wooden hut with other carriers and stands up every morning at two o'clock, because the sulphur also pours out at night, where his characteristic yellow color shines blue in the darkness.
Challenging the shadows, he climbs into the crater in the light of a small headlight on his helmet, which he bought from his own money.
About 400 carriers load the baskets on their shoulders on the crater floor with sulphur.
Despite its large profits, the mining company has not mechanized the mining of sulphur in order to save costs, and does not provide any equipment to the carriers who work on their own account and are paid by weight.
You will also not receive a share of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) supplement per camera, which the guards of this nature park, along with the entrance fee of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), require from the tourists who come to photograph the volcano and the human carrier.
"This work is for the animals and not for the human beings" protests Madrusin, a tribal, 42-year-old carrier who has been working at Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
He is able to carry up to 110 kg and assures that he continues, "as long as it goes" because he needs the money for raising his three children between 10 and 18 years of age.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano was my whole life.
Even if the sulfur burns the throat and the eyes itch when the wind suddenly turns and the miners stick into the thick columns that rise from the crater, the men are so hard that no one complains about serious diseases ... of course, except for the usual breathing problems, arthritis, pain in the knees and blisters on the shoulders that have deformed themselves from the weight of the basket.
With the basket on his back, with its 53 years, Unainik is only able to carry 50 kg.
Every day he and his companions break 15 tons of sulphur from the volcano, which are transported by three trucks over a goat path between the bushes to the camp in Tamansari in 18 kilometres.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano was my whole life," explains Unainik, opening his mouth wide, with some teeth missing.
Of his five children, the elder also works as a sulphur carrier at the age of 30.
Time passes, but poverty keeps generation after generation in one of the toughest occupations in the world: those who work as human donkeys on Kawah Ijen.
