Héctor "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
Héctor "Hetin" Reyes, the world-bummer of basketball, was connected to basketball for more than 60 years and has travelled the whole world.
Few in Puerto Rico have such a large spiritual collection of the history of the country's basketball as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
Before being tied to the wheelchair by a stroke in 2008, Rexes was part of this sport for six years, whether as a player of lower classes, player of the first national league, agent and leader of the BSN with the Vaqueros de Bayamón or president of the basketball association.
"I spent my life putting on a lot of hats in basketball, even several at the same time when I was President of the BSN, Chief Executive of the National Team and President of the Association in the 1990s," Reyes recalled when visiting Primera Hora at his home in Bayamón, where he lives with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"Basketball was my life."
Reyes does not exaggerate with this statement.
The walls of his house are almost all decorated with photos and memories of his long career and testify to them.
Bayamón in the heart
The most emotional memories are those that recall his time with the Vaqueros from the mid-50s as a player until 1982, where he celebrated his 15th anniversary as co-manager or managing director of the club.
"These were my best years that I enjoyed most because I was allowed to be part of eight of the Vaqueros championships since 1967 as Managing Director, Co-Chairman or Trainer.
It was many fulfilling years, including the five consecutive championships from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye to a championship in 1981, the year of Jerome Mincy's debut at BSN.
From then on, "Cuco" took over Ortiz, who was a very good administrator," says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who worked here as a coach and worked at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), said: "I have a very powerful and 2 m large player.
Do you want him?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico ever had.
Bartow then recommended the freelance specialist Raymond Gausse, who was one of our best pitchers.
I remember how he said that if Mincy had allowed a championship for Bayamon, Gausse would take care of another one.
The Vaqueros Championship with Gausse was awarded to him, but already out of a distance, because he was already in the top position of the Association in 1988.
At that time he preferred to enjoy his executions and those of Mincy in the national team.
I remember when we first won against the United States at the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we took fourth place, which should have been bronze, if not that Canadian referee who had allowed us to repeat the last move for the second time, Reyes said.
Was this group of the 1990 World Cup the best national team you've ever seen?
She is one of the best, as was the one who won the 2004 Olympics against the Dream Team.
But my favorite is the team of the 1991 pan-American games in Cuba, where we won gold and offered the team of the United States a fight, as they did when they won against us at the world championship bronze.
Not only were Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), but also the young players (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not attend in 1990 because of a knee injury.
A team that was perhaps not the best in terms of personalities, but with which we won a gold medal and which brought us great joy, was that of the 1995 pre-Olympic Tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players such as "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourruitin as a substitute for the locked players due to the events on the Pan-American games in Mar del Plata, we won the gold medal against every prognosis.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
That was no doubt Piculín Ortiz.
His figures at the level of international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated on this level as much as Piculín.
And this, without taking into account his career in the different leagues in which he played.
Who was the best coach from Puerto Rico?
That is a difficult question.
We had a number of good trainers like Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
Of the boys, I like Leo Arill's work.
What do you think is the best you've achieved in the League?
I was part of the most successful era of the national team from 1988 to 1995, which included the BSN at the beginning of the 1990s up to 17 teams in one season.
What else do you have to do?
There are things I would have introduced, such as the regionalisation of the lower categories.
That the boys play in Ponce e.g. only in their territory and only meet in the national playoffs on teams from other corners of the island.
Today, the children make unnecessary travels and games.
At least I see the result of the required training and courses for trainers, table officials and referees.
I'm proud of that.
What are you doing today?
I like to listen to music, watch videos of music of my time in YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren and occasionally go to a basketball game.
And of course I enjoy the company of my wife Isabel, who was always with me.
Larry Hagman is dead.
Larry Hagman was born on 21 September 1931 in Forth Worth (Texas) and became world famous with his role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R". in the television series "Dallas", where he played a unscrupulous, unscrupulous and manipulous businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as the oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, is dead.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who came back this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died Friday afternoon due to cancer complications according to a family press release to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., producer of "Dallas".
"Larry was back in his beloved birthplace Dallas, where he once again played the iconic role he liked most," said the family.
The family of Larry and his closest friends were with him in Dallas for the celebration of the Thanksgiving.
Linda Gray, who played the role of his wife in the original and subsequent series, was with Hagman when he died in Dallas Hospital, said her journalist Jeffrey Lane.
He made everyone who knew him happy.
He was creative, generous, funny, funny, loving and talented, and I will miss him very much.
"He was an original person and lived life in full accord," said Gray in a communication.
Hagman was diagnosed with liver cirrhosis in 1992, and he admitted that he had been drinking a lot over the years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was detected in his liver, and he underwent a transplant.
In the years before "Dallas" Hagman became known on television as a nice guy from 1965 to 1970 with the sitcom "Magnificent Jeannie" at the NBC television station.
There he played the astronaut Tony Nelson, whose life is put on the head when he meets an attractive "Jinn" (played by Barbara Eden) who will live with him at home.
He was also an actor of two comedies that were broadcast only for a short time, such as The Good Life (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His cinema works included well-rated roles in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was his masterful interpretation of the adorable J.R. that made Hagman a superstar.
The dramatic series of the CBS television chain about the Ewing-Clan and other figures in its surroundings was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The advertisement "Who shot at J.R.?", which was supposed to create expectation for an episode full of emotions, where Hagmann's figure was almost killed, led to international speculation, and millions of dollars were bet in bets.
The series thus reached an audience record at that time.
When the answer was announced in a chapter in November 1990, it was seen by an average of 41 million spectators who turned the "Dallas" into the second most viewed entertainment program since the end of 1983, which had 50 million spectators.
It was Kristin, the sister-in-law of J.R. (interpreted by Mary Crosby) who had shot.
